The main formula electricians use for current is from Ohm’s law:  
\(\displaystyle I = \frac{V}{R}\)[5][7]

- \(I\) = current in amperes (A)  
- \(V\) = voltage in volts (V)  
- \(R\) = resistance in ohms \(\Omega\)[7][5]

Another useful relationship is with charge and time:  
\(\displaystyle I = \frac{Q}{t}\) where \(Q\) is charge in coulombs (C) and \(t\) is time in seconds (s).[3][6]

